for training where Re(·) and Im(·) are real and imaginary parts. Reference images are acquired with 2.5× prospective (during acquisition) undersampling and reconstructed with an iterative SENSE r­ econstruction52. Input and reference images are normalized to unit interval. Testing is then performed on prospectively undersampled data.
CINENet reconstructs an aliasing-free image ρ ∈ CNxNyNzNt where Nx, Ny, Nz describe the 3D spatial dimensions and Nt the dynamic temporal cardiac phases. The input to the network is the complex-valued sensitivity weighted coil-combined zero-filled undersampled image ρu ∈ CNxNyNzNt with spatial matrix size Nx = 112, Ny = 160, Nz = 44 and Nt = 16 cardiac phases, as well as the acquired k-space ν ∈ CNxMyMzNtNCh with NCh = 14 receiver coils after coil compression and the VD-CASPR undersampling mask φ ∈ ZM×N extracted from ν , with M ≪ N, M = NxMyMzNt NCh, N = NxNyNz Nt NCh . The coil sensitivity maps S ∈ CN×N are obtained from the time-averaged fully sampled calibration center region in ν by E­ SPIRIT53 with virtual coil compression of initially 25–30 MR receiver coils (depending on field of view placement) to a common size of NCh = 14.
In the reconstruction, we assume that 3D cardiac CINE images contain a rich amount of redundancy on a spatial (between and within receptive fields of a given spatial voxel) and temporal (between cardiac phases) scale. The overall unconstrained MR reconstruction problem is given by

